## Avaamo CLI Guide For IDE Agents

- Prefer the `avaamo` command from the terminal `PATH`. In VS Code/Cursor workspaces opened through the Avaamo extension, new integrated terminals also receive `AVAAMO_CLI_PATH` and `AVAAMO_CLI_BIN_DIR` for the packaged CLI.
- Some IDE agents, including chat-side command runners, do not inherit another extension's terminal `PATH` or environment variables. If `avaamo` is not on `PATH`, try the workspace-local launcher `./.avaamo/bin/avaamo <args>`. The Avaamo extension writes this launcher when it sees an Avaamo workspace and rewrites it after extension upgrades.
- Auth-required CLI commands can use the Avaamo extension's device-local auth cache at `~/.avaamo/dashboard-auth.json` when token/cookie environment variables are missing. Do not open, print, copy, commit, or summarize that cache; if auth fails, ask the developer to refresh or switch accounts in the Avaamo Account panel.
- If `./.avaamo/bin/avaamo` is missing but `AVAAMO_CLI_PATH` is set, run commands as `node "$AVAAMO_CLI_PATH" <args>`.
- If no CLI path is available, do not guess global install locations. Offer a human-clicked Avaamo extension action button or tell the developer to use the Command Palette action, such as `Avaamo: Diff`, `Avaamo: Push Dry Run`, `Avaamo: Chat Check`, or `Avaamo: Push Changes`.
- Use `avaamo docs --render` for complete CLI documentation and `avaamo --help` for a compact command list.
- This folder is already a pulled dashboard agent workspace. Do not create another dashboard agent unless the human explicitly asks.
- To create a new dashboard agent when asked, use the extension command `Avaamo: Create Agent` or ask the human to run `avaamo bot create --name "<agent name>" --description "<description>" --out <folder> --json`. The dashboard UI calls it an agent; the CLI subcommand is still `bot create` for API compatibility.
- To pull an existing dashboard agent when asked, use the extension command `Avaamo: Pull Agent` or run `avaamo pull --bot-id <dashboard agent id> --out <folder>`.
- To merge dashboard changes into the currently open workspace when asked, offer the human-clicked extension command `Avaamo: Pull & Merge` wired to `avaamo.pullMerge`, or run `avaamo pull --merge` only after an explicit human request.
- Safe inspection commands for IDE agents: `avaamo docs --render`, `avaamo --help`, `avaamo status`, `avaamo diff`, `avaamo push --dry-run`, and `avaamo chat --check`.
- Human-explicit test commands: only run live `avaamo chat`, `avaamo serve`, `avaamo regression create`, `avaamo regression sample`, `avaamo regression ui`, or `avaamo regression --input <csv>` when the developer asks for that exact kind of testing/generation.
- Human-explicit debug commands: only run `avaamo debug errors`, `avaamo debug history <n>`, `avaamo debug conversation <url-or-id>`, or `avaamo debug events <conversation_session_id>` when the developer asks to fetch dashboard diagnostics. These commands write ignored artifacts under `.avaamo/debug/` by default.
- Human-only deploy command: never run `avaamo push` automatically. Offer the human-clicked `Avaamo: Push Changes` / `Push to Avaamo` action wired to `avaamo.push`, or tell the developer to run `avaamo push --lock --build` after review.
- Regression CSV workflow: create a draft with `avaamo regression create --output regression/smoke.csv --scenarios 10`, review/edit the CSV, run it with `avaamo regression --input regression/smoke.csv`, and inspect results with the `Avaamo: Open Regression UI` IDE action or `avaamo regression ui`. A blank template can be generated with `avaamo regression sample --output regression/sample.csv`.
- Regression input columns include `scenario_id`, `sequence_number`, `user_message`, `expected_response`, `match_mode`, `expected_response_type`, `expected_response_types`, `expected_rich_json`, and `notes`. Use `match_mode=semantic` for most cases and reserve rich JSON expectations for stable visible UI such as quick replies, cards, carousels, lists, and sources.
- For digital form checks, use `expected_response_types=input_form`, assert stable form labels in `expected_rich_json`, and use a follow-up turn with `form_values` to submit the form.
- Prompt-skill tools live in `prompt-skills/<skill>/functions/*.js` with optional matching `*.schema.json` and `*.meta.json` files. Dashboard JavaScript resources live in `js-files/`, `handlers/`, `callbacks/`, `feedback/`, and `settings/common_js_code.js`.


